<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto">

## introduction

<a href="#introduction" id="user-content-introduction" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: introduction"><img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="octicon octicon-link" /></a>

</div>

htmx allows you to access <a href="https://htmx.org/docs#ajax" rel="nofollow">AJAX</a>, <a href="https://htmx.org/docs#css_transitions" rel="nofollow">CSS Transitions</a>, <a href="https://htmx.org/extensions/ws/" rel="nofollow">WebSockets</a> and <a href="https://htmx.org/extensions/sse/" rel="nofollow">Server Sent Events</a> directly in HTML, using <a href="https://htmx.org/reference#attributes" rel="nofollow">attributes</a>, so you can build <a href="https://htmx.org/examples" rel="nofollow">modern user interfaces</a> with the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HATEOAS" rel="nofollow">simplicity</a> and <a href="https://www.ics.uci.edu/~fielding/pubs/dissertation/rest_arch_style.htm" rel="nofollow">power</a> of hypertext

htmx is small (<a href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/htmx.org/dist/" rel="nofollow">~14k min.gz'd</a>), [dependency-free](https://github.com/bigskysoftware/htmx/blob/master/package.json) & <a href="https://htmx.org/extensions" rel="nofollow">extendable</a>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto">

## motivation

<a href="#motivation" id="user-content-motivation" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: motivation"><img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="octicon octicon-link" /></a>

</div>

- Why should only `<a>` and `<form>` be able to make HTTP requests?
- Why should only `click` & `submit` events trigger them?
- Why should only GET & POST be available?
- Why should you only be able to replace the *entire* screen?

By removing these arbitrary constraints htmx completes HTML as a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext" rel="nofollow">hypertext</a>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto">

## quick start

<a href="#quick-start" id="user-content-quick-start" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: quick start"><img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="octicon octicon-link" /></a>

</div>

<div class="highlight highlight-text-html-basic notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" snippet-clipboard-copy-content="  &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/htmx.org@2.0.8/dist/htmx.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
  &lt;!-- have a button POST a click via AJAX --&gt;
  &lt;button hx-post=&quot;/clicked&quot; hx-swap=&quot;outerHTML&quot;&gt;
    Click Me
  &lt;/button&gt;">

      <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/htmx.org@2.0.8/dist/htmx.min.js"></script>
      <!-- have a button POST a click via AJAX -->
      <button hx-post="/clicked" hx-swap="outerHTML">
        Click Me
      </button>

</div>

The <a href="https://htmx.org/attributes/hx-post" rel="nofollow"><code>hx-post</code></a> and <a href="https://htmx.org/attributes/hx-swap" rel="nofollow"><code>hx-swap</code></a> attributes tell htmx:

> "When a user clicks on this button, issue an AJAX request to /clicked, and replace the entire button with the response"

htmx is the successor to <a href="http://intercoolerjs.org" rel="nofollow">intercooler.js</a>

<div class="markdown-heading" dir="auto">

### installing as a node package

<a href="#installing-as-a-node-package" id="user-content-installing-as-a-node-package" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: installing as a node package"><img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="octicon octicon-link" /></a>

<div class="snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" snippet-clipboard-copy-content="npm install htmx.org --save">

``` notranslate

```

</div>

Note there is an old broken package called `htmx`. This is `htmx.org`.

### hacking guide

<a href="#hacking-guide" id="user-content-hacking-guide" class="anchor" aria-label="Permalink: hacking guide"><img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="octicon octicon-link" /></a>

</div>

To develop htmx locally, you will need to install the development dependencies.

Run:

<div class="snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" snippet-clipboard-copy-content="npm install">

``` notranslate
npm install
```

</div>

Then, run a web server in the root.

This is easiest with:

<div class="snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" snippet-clipboard-copy-content="npx serve">

``` notranslate
npx serve
```

</div>

You can then run the test suite by navigating to:

<a href="http://0.0.0.0:3000/test/" rel="nofollow">http://0.0.0.0:3000/test/</a>

At this point you can modify `/src/htmx.js` to add features, and then add tests in the appropriate area under `/test`.

- `/test/index.html` - the root test page from which all other tests are included
- `/test/attributes` - attribute specific tests
- `/test/core` - core functionality tests
- `/test/core/regressions.js` - regression tests
- `/test/ext` - extension tests
- `/test/manual` - manual tests that cannot be automated

htmx uses the <a href="https://mochajs.org/" rel="nofollow">mocha</a> testing framework, the <a href="https://www.chaijs.com/" rel="nofollow">chai</a> assertion framework and <a href="https://sinonjs.org/releases/v9/fake-xhr-and-server/" rel="nofollow">sinon</a> to mock out AJAX requests. They are all OK.
